I created a new thread simply using:

```cs
Thread thread = new Thread(Execute);
thread.Start(cancellationToken);
```

where the `Execute` method is as defined as:

```cs
private void Execute(object data)
{
	CancellationToken cancellationToken = (CancellationToken)data;

	while (_run && !cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
	{
		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}: Create process for {Path.GetFileName(_appSettings.Service)}.");
		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}: Current directory: {Environment.CurrentDirectory}");

		using (_process = new Process())
		{
			try
			{
				_processDisposed = false;
				_process.Disposed += Process_Disposed;

				_process.StartInfo.FileName = _appSettings.Service;
				_process.StartInfo.Arguments = _appSettings.Arguments;

				_process.StartInfo.UseShellExecute = false;
				_process.StartInfo.CreateNoWindow = true;
				_process.Start();

				_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}({_appSettings.ServiceName}): - Process started");

				_process.WaitForExit();
			}
			catch (Exception ex)
			{
				_logger.LogError(ex, $"Task.Run #00");
			}
		}

		_process = null;

		throw new Exception("We have failed!");

		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}({_appSettings.ServiceName}): - Process stopped");

		if (_run && !cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
		{
			Thread.Sleep(_appSettings.RestartDelay * 1000);
		}
	}
}
```

When the exception occurs within the `using` statement, the line number is correctly reported.  However, anywhere else within the `while` statement, the StackTrace will show the line number of the `while` statement, and not the actual line number of where the exception occurred.

